# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anna-j-harrison
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is employed as an analytical chemistry tool to determine the presence of a particular substance in a sample and, in many cases, to quantify the amount of the substance present.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Infrared and ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy are particularly common in analytical applications.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in studies of molecular and atomic physics, astronomical spectroscopy and remote sensing.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] There is a wide range of experimental approaches for measuring absorption spectra.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The most common arrangement is to direct a generated beam of radiation at a sample and detect the intensity of the radiation that passes through it.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The transmitted energy can be used to calculate the absorption.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The source, sample arrangement and detection technique vary significantly depending on the frequency range and the purpose of the experiment.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] A material's absorption spectrum is the fraction of incident radiation absorbed by the material over a range of frequencies of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The absorption spectrum is primarily determined by the atomic and molecular composition of the material.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Radiation is more likely to be absorbed at frequencies that match the energy difference between two quantum mechanical states of the molecules.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The absorption that occurs due to a transition between two states is referred to as an absorption line and a spectrum is typically composed of many lines.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The frequencies at which absorption lines occur, as well as their relative intensities, primarily depend on the electronic and molecular structure of the sample.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The frequencies will also depend on the interactions between molecules in the sample, the crystal structure in solids, and on several environmental factors (e.g., temperature, pressure, electric field, magnetic field).
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The lines will also have a width and shape that are primarily determined by the spectral density or the density of states of the system.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption lines are typically classified by the nature of the quantum mechanical change induced in the molecule or atom.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Rotational lines, for instance, occur when the rotational state of a molecule is changed.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Rotational lines are typically found in the microwave spectral region.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Vibrational lines correspond to changes in the vibrational state of the molecule and are typically found in the infrared region.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Electronic lines correspond to a change in the electronic state of an atom or molecule and are typically found in the visible and ultraviolet region.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] X-ray absorptions are associated with the excitation of inner shell electrons in atoms.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] These changes can also be combined (e.g. rotation–vibration transitions), leading to new absorption lines at the combined energy of the two changes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The energy associated with the quantum mechanical change primarily determines the frequency of the absorption line but the frequency can be shifted by several types of interactions.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Electric and magnetic fields can cause a shift.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Interactions with neighboring molecules can cause shifts.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For instance, absorption lines of the gas phase molecule can shift significantly when that molecule is in a liquid or solid phase and interacting more strongly with neighboring molecules.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The width and shape of absorption lines are determined by the instrument used for the observation, the material absorbing the radiation and the physical environment of that material.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] It is common for lines to have the shape of a Gaussian or Lorentzian distribution.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] It is also common for a line to be described solely by its intensity and width instead of the entire shape being characterized.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The integrated intensity—obtained by integrating the area under the absorption line—is proportional to the amount of the absorbing substance present.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The intensity is also related to the temperature of the substance and the quantum mechanical interaction between the radiation and the absorber.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] This interaction is quantified by the transition moment and depends on the particular lower state the transition starts from, and the upper state it is connected to.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The width of absorption lines may be determined by the spectrometer used to record it.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] A spectrometer has an inherent limit on how narrow a line it can resolve and so the observed width may be at this limit.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] If the width is larger than the resolution limit, then it is primarily determined by the environment of the absorber.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] A liquid or solid absorber, in which neighboring molecules strongly interact with one another, tends to have broader absorption lines than a gas.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Increasing the temperature or pressure of the absorbing material will also tend to increase the line width.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] It is also common for several neighboring transitions to be close enough to one another that their lines overlap and the resulting overall line is therefore broader yet.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption and transmission spectra represent equivalent information and one can be calculated from the other through a mathematical transformation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] A transmission spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is weakest because more light is transmitted through the sample.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] An absorption spectrum will have its maximum intensities at wavelengths where the absorption is strongest.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Emission is a process by which a substance releases energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Emission can occur at any frequency at which absorption can occur, and this allows the absorption lines to be determined from an emission spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The emission spectrum will typically have a quite different intensity pattern from the absorption spectrum, though, so the two are not equivalent.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The absorption spectrum can be calculated from the emission spectrum using Einstein coefficients.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The scattering and reflection spectra of a material are influenced by both its refractive index and its absorption spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] In an optical context, the absorption spectrum is typically quantified by the extinction coefficient, and the extinction and index coefficients are quantitatively related through the Kramers–Kronig relations.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Therefore, the absorption spectrum can be derived from a scattering or reflection spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] This typically requires simplifying assumptions or models, and so the derived absorption spectrum is an approximation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is useful in chemical analysis because of its specificity and its quantitative nature.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The specificity of absorption spectra allows compounds to be distinguished from one another in a mixture, making absorption spectroscopy useful in wide variety of applications.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For instance, Infrared gas analyzers can be used to detect pollutants in the air, distinguishing them from nitrogen, oxygen, water, and other expected constituents.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The specificity also allows unknown samples to be identified by comparing a measured spectrum with a library of reference spectra.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] In many cases, qualitative information about a sample can be determined even if it is not in a library.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Infrared spectra, for instance, have characteristic absorption bands that indicate if carbon-hydrogen or carbon-oxygen bonds are present.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] An absorption spectrum can be quantitatively related to the amount of material present using the Beer–Lambert law .
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Determining the absolute concentration of a compound requires knowledge of the compound's absorption coefficient.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The absorption coefficient for some compounds is available in reference sources, and it can also be determined by measuring the spectrum of a calibration standard with a known concentration of the target compound.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] One of the unique advantages of spectroscopy as an analytical technique is that measurements can be made without bringing the instrument and sample into contact.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Radiation that travels between a sample and an instrument will contain the spectral information, so the measurement can be made remotely.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Remote spectral sensing is valuable in many situations.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For example, measurements can be made in toxic or hazardous environments without placing an operator or instrument at risk.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Also, sample material does not have to be brought into contact with the instrument—preventing possible cross contamination.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Remote spectral measurements present several challenges compared to laboratory measurements.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The space in between the sample of interest and the instrument may also have spectral absorptions.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] These absorptions can mask or confound the absorption spectrum of the sample.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] These background interferences may also vary over time.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The source of radiation in remote measurements is often an environmental source, such as sunlight or the thermal radiation from a warm object, and this makes it necessary to distinguish spectral absorption from changes in the source spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] To simplify these challenges, differential optical absorption spectroscopy has gained some popularity, as it focusses on differential absorption features and omits broad-band absorption such as aerosol extinction and extinction due to rayleigh scattering.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] This method is applied to ground-based, airborne, and satellite-based measurements.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Some ground-based methods provide the possibility to retrieve tropospheric and stratospheric trace gas profiles.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Astronomical spectroscopy is a particularly significant type of remote spectral sensing.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] In this case, the objects and samples of interest are so distant from earth that electromagnetic radiation is the only means available to measure them.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Astronomical spectra contain both absorption and emission spectral information.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy has been particularly important for understanding interstellar clouds and determining that some of them contain molecules.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Absorption spectroscopy is also employed in the study of extrasolar planets.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Detection of extrasolar planets by transit photometry also measures their absorption spectrum and allows for the determination of the planet's atmospheric composition, temperature, pressure, and scale height, and hence allows also for the determination of the planet's mass.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Theoretical models, principally quantum mechanical models, allow for the absorption spectra of atoms and molecules to be related to other physical properties such as electronic structure, atomic or molecular mass, and molecular geometry.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Therefore, measurements of the absorption spectrum are used to determine these other properties.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Microwave spectroscopy, for example, allows for the determination of bond lengths and angles with high precision.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] In addition, spectral measurements can be used to determine the accuracy of theoretical predictions.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For example, the Lamb shift measured in the hydrogen atomic absorption spectrum was not expected to exist at the time it was measured.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Its discovery spurred and guided the development of quantum electrodynamics, and measurements of the Lamb shift are now used to determine the fine-structure constant.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The most straightforward approach to absorption spectroscopy is to generate radiation with a source, measure a reference spectrum of that radiation with a detector and then re-measure the sample spectrum after placing the material of interest in between the source and detector.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The two measured spectra can then be combined to determine the material's absorption spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The reference spectrum will be affected in the same way, though, by these experimental conditions and therefore the combination yields the absorption spectrum of the material alone.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] A wide variety of radiation sources are employed in order to cover the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For spectroscopy, it is generally desirable for a source to cover a broad swath of wavelengths in order to measure a broad region of the absorption spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Some sources inherently emit a broad spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Examples of these include globars or other black body sources in the infrared, mercury lamps in the visible and ultraviolet, and X-ray tubes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] One recently developed, novel source of broad spectrum radiation is synchrotron radiation, which covers all of these spectral regions.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Other radiation sources generate a narrow spectrum, but the emission wavelength can be tuned to cover a spectral range.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Examples of these include klystrons in the microwave region and lasers across the infrared, visible, and ultraviolet region (though not all lasers have tunable wavelengths).
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The detector employed to measure the radiation power will also depend on the wavelength range of interest.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Most detectors are sensitive to a fairly broad spectral range and the sensor selected will often depend more on the sensitivity and noise requirements of a given measurement.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Examples of detectors common in spectroscopy include heterodyne receivers in the microwave, bolometers in the millimeter-wave and infrared, mercury cadmium telluride and other cooled semiconductor detectors in the infrared, and photodiodes and photomultiplier tubes in the visible and ultraviolet.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] If both the source and the detector cover a broad spectral region, then it is also necessary to introduce a means of resolving the wavelength of the radiation in order to determine the spectrum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Often a spectrograph is used to spatially separate the wavelengths of radiation so that the power at each wavelength can be measured independently.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] It is also common to employ interferometry to determine the spectrum—Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy is a widely used implementation of this technique.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] Two other issues that must be considered in setting up an absorption spectroscopy experiment include the optics used to direct the radiation and the means of holding or containing the sample material (called a cuvette or cell).
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For most UV, visible, and NIR measurements the use of precision quartz cuvettes are necessary.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] In both cases, it is important to select materials that have relatively little absorption of their own in the wavelength range of interest.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] The absorption of other materials could interfere with or mask the absorption from the sample.
[src:anna-j-harrison/absorption-spectra] For instance, in several wavelength ranges it is necessary to measure the sample under vacuum or in a noble gas environment because gases in the atmosphere have interfering absorption features.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He died on 27 January 1991 in Bethlehem, Pennsylvania.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He attended the Lehigh University, where he completed his B.S. degree in chemical engineering in 1936 and an M.S. degree in 1938.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He completed his Ph.D. in physical chemistry from Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1941.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He became the president of the American Chemical Society in 1981.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He also served as the provost and vice president of Lehigh University.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-c-zettlemoyer] He published more than 230 technical articles and held 10 patents.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:anna-j-harrison/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:anna-j-harrison/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Anna Jane Harrison was born in Benton City, Missouri, on December 23, 1912.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Her parents, Albert Harrison and Mary Katherine Jones Harrison, were farmers.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Her father died when she was seven, leaving her mother to manage the family farm and to care for Harrison and her elder brother.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She first became interested in science while attending high school in Mexico, Missouri.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She received her B.A. in 1933 in chemistry, a B.A. in 1935 in education, a M.A. in 1937 in chemistry, and a Ph.D. in 1940 in physical chemistry, all from the University of Missouri in Columbia, Missouri.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Her Ph.D. dissertation focused on reactions involving sodium ketyls.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] While working towards her master's degree in chemistry, Harrison taught elementary school at the one-room country school in Audrain County, Missouri, where she had attended school as a child.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Sophie Newcomb Memorial College, the coordinate women's college of Tulane University from 1940 to 1945.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] In 1942 while on leave from teaching during World War II, Harrison conducted secret wartime research at the University of Missouri.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] In 1944, she conducted research on toxic smoke for the National Defense Research Committee, the A.J.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Griner Co. in Kansas City, Missouri and Corning Glass Works in Corning, New York.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] This work was instrumental in the creation of smoke-detecting field kits for the United States Army.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She received the Frank Forrest Award from the American Ceramic Society for her research.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] In 1945, she joined the chemistry department at Mount Holyoke College as an assistant professor.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She came to Holyoke to work with professor and researcher Emma P.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She became a full professor in the department in 1950 and served as the chair from 1960 to 1966.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She retired from Mount Holyoke College in 1979.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Harrison's research focused on the structure of organic compounds and their interaction with light, particularly in the ultraviolet and far ultraviolet bands.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She served on the National Science Board from 1972 to 1978.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] In 1978 she became the first female president of the American Chemical Society.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She also served as president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1983.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She wrote articles for *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, *Chemical & Engineering News*, and *Encyclopædia Britannica*.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She served on the editorial boards of the National Science Teachers Association's Journal of College Science Teaching and Chemical & Engineering News.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] In 1989 she co-authored a textbook with Mount Holyoke College colleague Edwin S.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] Weaver entitled *Chemistry: A Search to Understand*.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She was interested in working towards increased funding for science education by state and federal agencies and promoting the cause of women in science.
[src:anna-j-harrison/anna-j-harrison] She died in Holyoke, Massachusetts at the age of eighty-five from a stroke.
